#: persons-identity.rst:58
msgid "Entering ``person`` defines the claim and defines the relevant fields to be used in further data entry about a :ref:`person`. For quality assurance purposes, entering ``person`` should create an error if there is any entry for fields tied to other claim types, such as :ref:`posting`."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:61
msgid "status:meta"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:67
msgid "A field that classifies the data in the claim."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:82
msgid "``:claim/statuses``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:87
msgid "``accepted``, ``conflict``, ``work_needed``, ``issue``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:92
msgid "Claims are marked ``accepted`` when all of the data can be entered in accordance with the guidance of this handbook. The ``conflict`` flag is used whenever a claim conflicts with another claim (or claims) and a review of citations show it to be the incorrect or false claim (see :ref:`Citations with both Accepted and Conflicted Information` for guidance when one claim from a citation contains both ``accepted`` and ``conflict`` information). A :ref:`public_notes:meta <person-public-notes>` should always accompany any ``conflict`` claim."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:94
msgid "If the data itself cannot be brought into the SFM standard the flag ``issue`` should be used. Finally, if the current citations cannot establish whether a claim should be flagged as ``accepted`` or ``conflict`` then the flag ``work_needed`` should be used as additional research is needed."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:97
msgid "researcher:meta"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:103
msgid "Field for initials or other identifier of researcher who last entered data for the claim."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:118
msgid "``:meta/researchers``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:123
msgid "``TW``, ``Jane_Doe``, ``G1``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:128
msgid "Every researcher should use this field to mark the claims that they have entered. Anytime a researcher modifies any data for an existing claim they should update this field so that any questions can be directed to the right person and the flow of work can be better tracked."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:131
msgid "internal_comments:meta"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:137
msgid "A field for temporary comments or notes for the researcher or research team working on the claim."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:147 persons-identity.rst:254 persons-identity.rst:290 persons-identity.rst:505 persons-identity.rst:539 persons-identity.rst:573 persons-identity.rst:607 persons-identity.rst:641 persons-identity.rst:675 persons-identity.rst:709 persons-identity.rst:743 persons-identity.rst:777 persons-identity.rst:812
msgid "This attribute is optional."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:152
msgid "``:meta/internal-comments``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:157
msgid "``Come back to this to determine date for claim``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:162
msgid "Researchers may use this field to make temporary notes or leave temporary comments intended for others in the research team about a claim. These should eventually be addressed and the field cleared by the researcher or research team. If the claim needs an explanatory note or comment to be better understood, then that should be entered in the :ref:`public_notes:meta <person-public-notes>` field."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:165
msgid "citation:refs:claim"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:171
msgid "Field unique 32 character code assigned to citation(s) evidencing the claim."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:176 persons-identity.rst:211
msgid "String in UUID format"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:186
msgid "``:claim/citation:refs``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:191
msgid "``69dba35b-2b70-47cf-bfda-f80225f652c6``, ``4e99308c-f9c0-49e8-b97b-14c1e7bcb99d;bedf57b2-c20b-41e3-9dcf-b7b065eaa3b7``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:196
msgid "Every claim must have at least one citation to evidence the data in the claim. When two or more citations are needed to evidence a claim then a corresponding explanatory note should be entered in the :ref:`public_notes:meta <person-public-notes>` field. This field is for the Universally Unique Identifier (UUID) for each citation, found in the :ref:`source:access_point_id:admin` field in the Sources sheet. When multiple citations are needed every UUID should be semi-colon separated."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:200
msgid "about_entity:ref:claim"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:206
msgid "A unique 32 character code assigned to each entity in the dataset."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:221
msgid "``:claim/about-entity:ref``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:226
msgid "``521ebf18-f161-4ac9-8c72-5a246efa0458``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:231
msgid "Every entity has a Universally Unique Identifier (UUID) to distinguish it from any other entity. For a :ref:`person` this UUID distinguishes them from any other :ref:`person` in the dataset. This UUID is used in other fields to tie a :ref:`person` to a :ref:`posting` or :ref:`incident`."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:233
msgid "A :ref:`person` from one citation is never assumed to be the same :ref:`person` from another citation based on an exact or near match of their name. Instead the :ref:`posting` is used to determine whether two people with the same or similar names are the same :ref:`person`. For example, if a citation states ``John Alfred Smith`` was commander of ``Police Station 1`` and another states ``John Smith`` was the commander of ``Police Station 1`` they would be treated as the same person given the match of :ref:`posting` as well as their similar names. However, if one citation stated ``John Alfred Smith`` was the commander of ``Police Station 2`` they would not be treated as the same person as the ``John Alfred Smith`` who was commander of ``Police Station 1`` since there is no match of a :ref:`posting`."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:235
msgid "Determining whether one :ref:`person` held multiple postings is based on some match of postings among different citations. For example, if one citation stated ``John Alfred Smith`` was commander of ``Police Station 1`` and another citation stated ``J. Smith`` was commander of ``Police Station 3`` there would be no match and these should be coded as two separate people each with their own :ref:`about_entity:ref:claim <person-about-entity>`. If then a third citation stated that during the career of ``John Smith`` he was commander of ``Police Station 1``, ``Police station 15`` and ``Police Station 3`` then all of these would be treated as the same person given the match of at least one :ref:`posting` across all citations and the similar names of the person in each citation."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:238
msgid "about_entity:name:qa"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:244
msgid "Field that provides human readable name for entity."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:259
msgid "n/a"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:264
msgid "``Ye Win Oo``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:269
msgid "This field provides a human readable counterpart to the :ref:`about_entity:ref:claim <person-about-entity>`` which combines the various elements of the claim into a single text field. This field can be manually added by a researcher or automatically populated by the system after import. For a :ref:`person` best practice is to use the :ref:`name:annotation <person-name-annotation>` in this field."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:274
msgid "name:annotation"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:280
msgid "Fullest name of the person as evidenced by citations. This may include a given name, surname, middle name(s), as well as other names depending on the specific context."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:285 persons-identity.rst:323 persons-identity.rst:466 persons-identity.rst:738 persons-identity.rst:772 persons-identity.rst:807
msgid "String"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:295
msgid "``:annotation/name``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:300
msgid "``Zeyar Aung``, ``Myo Moe Aung‡``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:305
msgid "As with all annotation fields, this field is the singular display name for the entity. For a :ref:`person` this field is only used if the citation evidences the fullest name of a person, which is defined as the name with the highest number of characters. Ranks, titles, or positions held should not be entered in this field as they are captured in other fields."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:307
msgid "This field can be dynamic and change with ongoing research. For example, a researcher investigating Myanmar may first come across citation ``9f01b1c1-563f-4b40-a534-b91c7e1a5062`` for the :ref:`person` of ``Zeya Aung`` (a name which has nine characters). This would be entered in :ref:`name:annotation <person-name-annotation>`. Next, they may come across another citation ``4c0aaa5d-a147-4f1c-91d8-46d005be1a04`` that evidences the same :ref:`person` but gives a name of ``Zayar Aung`` (with 10 characters). This longer which would be entered in :ref:`name:annotation <person-name-annotation>`. ``Zeya Aung`` in the previous entry tied to citation ``9f01b1c1-563f-4b40-a534-b91c7e1a5062`` would now be entered only in :ref`person:names:assertion`, and the :ref:`name:annotation <person-name-annotation>` for that entry would be cleared. Finally, the researcher may come across citation ``c0b4b224-6432-45a5-854d-148d76af0ffa`` which would evidence the name of ``Zeyar Aung`` (with 10 characters). As there are two names, both with 10 characters each, the researcher would use the agreement of the name starting with \"Zeya\" to evidence ``Zeyar Aung`` as the :ref:`name:annotation <person-name-annotation>`, and ``Zayar Aung`` in the previous entry tied to citation ``4c0aaa5d-a147-4f1c-91d8-46d005be1a04`` would be cleared."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:309
msgid "Occasionally there are two people who may be the same :ref:`person` due to a near or exact match of names, and lack of any conflicting information (such as :ref:`postings`, dates of birth or death, or any other career or biographical information), but no citations have been found to confirm they are the same :ref:`person`. In these cases the symbol ‡ can be applied after the last character in their :ref:`name:annotation <person-name-annotation>` to help visually identify them in their display name. A corresponding :ref:`public_notes:meta <person-public-notes>` should be entered to explain why the symbol ‡ has been used."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:312
msgid "person:names:assertion"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:318
msgid "Any name given for person from citation."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:333
msgid "``:assertion/person:names``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:338
msgid "``Virgilio Daniel Méndez Bazan``, ``Virgilio Daniel Mendez Bazán``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:343
msgid "Any name for a person used in the citation should be entered in this field. While the :ref:`name:annotation <person-name-annotation>` field is only used for a single, most complex value, this field is used for any name a citation uses for a person. Thus, this field serves to capture \"aliases\" of a person, which also includes any typos or misspellings that may exist in the citation."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:345
msgid "Ranks, titles, or positions held should not be entered in this field as they are captured in other fields."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:348
msgid "person:genders:assertion"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:354
msgid "Indicators of a person's sex or gender identity, as inferred from pronouns used in the text of available sources."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:359 persons-identity.rst:397
msgid "Open list, single choice."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:364 persons-identity.rst:402 persons-identity.rst:437 persons-identity.rst:471
msgid "This is a draft field, to be finalized."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:369
msgid "``:assertion/person:genders``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:374
msgid "``male``, ``female``, ``other``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:379
msgid "This attribute is used to capture data about the gender of a person, as determined only by the pronouns (\"her\", \"she\", \"his\", \"him\", etc.) used in any available textual sources about this person. Data entry based on these pronouns is based on the coding of pronouns as \"masculine\" for ``male`` and \"feminine\" for ``female`` from `Global Affairs at UC Davis <https://globalaffairs.ucdavis.edu/iae/graduate/language-tips/pronouns-and-gender>`_. We do not infer a person's gender from their name or images of them."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:381
msgid "Echoing the definition used in the `FOAF standard <http://xmlns.com/foaf/spec/#term_gender>`_, the :ref:`person:genders:assertion` attribute is not intended to capture the full range of possible biological, social and sexual associated with the word \"gender\". This attribute open to include alternatives that are expressed within the available sources about a person."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:383
msgid "Where the sources contain no textual indication about the person's gender, the attribute should be left blank."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:386
msgid "person:account_type:assertion"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:392
msgid "The name of an online platform or service on which the person holds an account."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:408
msgid "``:assertion/person:account-type``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:413
msgid "``facebook``, ``telegram``, ``youtube``"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:418
msgid "This attribute is used to record the name of the online platform of service on which a person holds an account. The name is chosen from a list of available platforms and services, which will be updated as required. Where a person has more than one account, on the same or different platforms, a new claim should be created."
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:421
msgid "person:account_id:assertion"
msgstr ""

#: persons-identity.rst:427
